      "content": "# Building a Terminal-Style Portfolio\n\nEver since I first started messing around with front-end development, I have longed to create\na unique and intersting portfolio. I first started off creating a basic hero card based portfolio\nyears back, but my tailwind/styling abilities were not very good so I never ended up publishing it.\n\nAbout a year ago, I decided to try again -- I created a linkedin-like profile based portfolio\nas an experiment into making a more customized profile where I could easily blog, update skills,\nlink them to projects and more. It had built-in live editing capabilites and more. But at the end of the\nday, it still felt very... clunky. Parts of it were very visualy interesting but it did not feel very\n\"unique\", and didnt really reflect who I am as an engineer. This project ended up getting published, but\nsince I was never in love with it, I did not keep it up to date -- so a few months later I decided to shelf\nit.\n\nFast forward to the start of 2026. I decided I wanted something that would stand out\nand showcase my personality as a developer. What better way than to build an\ninteractive terminal experience? I decided to pair my coding skills with the abilities of Claude Code to help\nbridge some of the gaps to help bring my idea alive. While it did involve a lot of \"vibe\" coding to get some\nof the terminal kinks working properly, it was 100 percent my vision from start to finish.\n\n## The Concept\n\nThe idea was simple: make a portfolio that feels like a real terminal—boot sequence, file-system navigation,\nand plenty to explore. I didn’t want something that just looked like a terminal; I wanted a functional one,\ncomplete with real commands and hidden features for anyone curious enough to poke around.\n\n## A Split Experience\n\nAs the experience came together, I realized something crucial: not everyone wants to navigate a portfolio through\na command line interface-especially visitors from non-technical backgrounds. While the terminal is a big part of\nwho I am as an engineer, accessibility and clarity still matter. To solve this, I decided to go  with a split\napproach that adds both a terminal and modern UI. On entry, visitors are presented with a split screen and the\nabilit to choose between an interactive terminal interface or a more traditional, modern portfolio layout. Both\npresent the same core information—projects, experience, skills, etc-but in very different ways. This approach\nkeeps the terminal as a fully-featured, playful experience for those who enjoy exploration, while also providing a\nstraightforward path for anyone who just wants to browse the content traditionally. The choice is left entirely\nto the user.\n\n## Technical Implementation\n\nThe portfolio is built with:\n- **Next.js 16** for the framework\n- **TypeScript** for type safety\n- **Tailwind CSS** for styling\n- **React hooks** for state management\n\n## Key Features\n\n### Terminal UI\n1. **Boot Sequence** - A dramatic initialization that sets the mood\n2. **Virtual File System** - Navigate through my experience like files\n3. **Real Commands** - ls, cd, cat, and more actually work\n4. **Easter Eggs** - Try `cowsay`, `matrix`, or `sudo rm -rf /`\n\n### Modern UI\n1. **Smooth Animations** - Motion-driven transitions and scroll effects throughout\n2. **Responsive Design** - Fully optimized for desktop, tablet, and mobile views\n3. **Interactive Filtering** - Filter projects and blog posts by tags and search\n4. **Section Navigation** - Sticky header with scroll-aware active section highlighting\n5. **Accessibility First** - Clean, readable layout for all visitors\n\n## Lessons Learned\n\nBuilding this taught me a lot about:\n- Creating immersive user experiences\n- Balancing creativity with usability\n- The importance of small details\n\nThe terminal aesthetic isn't just a gimmick—it's a statement about who I am as\na developer: someone who lives in the command line and loves what they do.\n"
